'''Health Advocate, Inc.''' is a national [[health advocacy]], [[patient advocacy]] and assistance company, serving more than 9,000 clients and 40+ million people and offering a spectrum of  services to help employers, employees and consumers navigate the healthcare system and facilitate members’ interactions with insurers and providers.<ref>Dorschner, John. “Healthcare advocacy experts aid workers.” Miami Herald 31 August 2010</ref> The privately held company was founded in 2001 by former [[Aetna]] executives<ref>Young, Lauren. “Advocates WhoHelp You Negotiate Healthcare.” BusinessWeek 22 October 2007</ref>  and is headquartered in [[Plymouth Meeting, Pennsylvania]]. The company employs registered nurses, medical directors and benefits specialists<ref>{{cite news|last=George|first=John|date=2–8 October 2009|title=Health Advocate has the answers to health questions|work=[[Philadelphia Business Journal]]|url=http://philadelphia.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/stories/2009/10/05/focus2.html|accessdate= February 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Heubeck|first=Elizabeth|date=30 November 2007|title=Personal health care advocates sell benefits expertise to firms|work=[[Baltimore Business Journal]]|url=http://baltimore.bizjournals.com/baltimore/stories/2007/12/03/focus1.html|accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref> who address a range of [[health care]] and [[health insurance]] issues.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wells|first=Susan J.|date=1 August 2006|title=Independent experts can help employees conquer mountains of medical paperwork, freeing HR to focus on other core concerns|work=[[Society for Human Resource Management#Publications and events|SHRM HR Magazine]]|url=http://moss07.shrm.org/Publications/hrmagazine/EditorialContent/Pages/0806SRwells.aspx|accessdate= February 15, 2010}}</ref> Personal Health Advocates work one-on-one with members to help them navigate the complicated world of health insurance and medical care. For example, Personal Health Advocates can help members locate providers, address errors on medical bills, answer questions about coverage denials and assist with insurance appeals.<ref>Guterl, Gail O. “Advocating for clients.” Advance for Nurses 9 June 2003</ref> 

The company's complementary solutions include Wellness Advocate, Benefits Gateway+Health Information Dashboards, EAP and Worklife, Pricing Decision Support, Personalized Health Communications, Chronic Care Management, and HR solutions. The company also offers a direct-to-consumer advocacy service, called [http://www.HealthProponent.com/ Health Proponent] to individuals who are not part of groups.

==Products and Services==
'''CORE ADVOCACY'''
*'''Clinical Assistance''' – specialized medical and pharmaceutical advice and research.<ref>Silverman, Ed. “Healthy Backing,” Human Resource Executive May 2003</ref>
For example: Helping members understand tests, treatments, and medications recommended or prescribed by physicians, facilitating the transfer of medical records, X-rays, and lab results before a scheduled appointment with a new physician, arranging for home-care equipment after discharge from a hospital, facilitating review of test results with another physician for confirmation of diagnosis, consolidating a multiple-day testing schedule for members with special needs, arranging hospice and other services for the terminally ill, facilitating transfer from a community hospital to a tertiary care facility.<ref>Diamond, Frank. “Plan Lets Ombudsman Go To Bat for Members,” Managed Care October 2004</ref>

*'''Administrative Assistance''' - resolving claims and benefits issues, and help finding assistance outside the health plan.<ref>“Former Aetna Execs See Growth in New Patient Advocacy Company.” Managed Care Week 29 July 2002</ref>
For example: Researching a member’s outstanding out-of-pocket responsibilities and resolving errors with providers and/or the member’s health plan, correcting balance-billing problems, correcting charges incorrectly applied to the member’s deductible, resolving eligibility problems and benefit and claim denials, coordinating benefits between dental, medical, worker’s compensation, and disability carriers, assuring correct application of provider network status, correcting errors in processing of “blind” network provider discounts, resolving coordination-of-benefits disputes between carriers, satisfying plan requests for copies of referrals, providing correct member insurance information to providers.<ref>Diamond, Frank. “Plan Lets Ombudsman Go To Bat for Members,” Managed Care October 2004</ref>  

'''COMPLEMENTARY SOLUTIONS'''
*'''Wellness Advocate''' - provides employers and other plan sponsors with a broad array of wellness solutions that help employees lose weight, get fit and make other healthy lifestyle changes. The program is designed to reduce risks of diseases, prompt employees to take an active role in their healthcare and make informed decisions about their healthcare. The program features access to live Wellness Coaches coupled with comprehensive, up-to-date health and wellness information.<ref>Cranshaw, Dave. “Gen Plumbing institutes long-term wellness plan.” Providence Business News 2–8 January 2006</ref>

*'''Employee Assistance Program (EAP)/ WorkLife''' - counseling and work/life services provide in-depth help to resolve healthcare and insurance-related issues.

*'''Enrollment Advocate''' - designed to help answer employees’ questions about health plan options and features during an organization’s annual open enrollment period. This ensures that enrollment runs smoothly and effortlessly.<ref>George, John. “Health Advocate has the answers to health questions.” The Philadelphia Business Journal 2–8 October 2009.</ref>

*'''Medical Bill Saver''' - help negotaiting discounts on non-covered or out-of-network medical claims.<ref>George, John. “Health Advocate has the answers to health questions.” The Philadelphia Business Journal 2–8 October 2009.</ref>

*'''Benefits Gateway+Health Information Dashboards''' - offer a personalized, integrated service that gets employees to the right benefit, quickly and efficiently, through a single toll-free number. The dashboards then use algorithms to interpret data from multiple sources and provide a snapshot of member information about benefits use and specific health indicators.<ref>George, John (2–8 October 2009). "Health Advocate has the answers to health questions". Philadelphia Business Journal. http://philadelphia.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/stories/2009/10/05/focus2.html. Retrieved February 15, 2010.</ref>

==Who is Covered?==
Employers generally offer the service to their employees as an added benefit and extension to their healthcare insurance plans. The employee’s immediate family is also covered. This includes spouses, dependent children, parents and parents-in-law.<ref>Rotenberg, Carl. “Health move,” The Times Herald 14 May 2003</ref> According to one client, [[Wawa Food Market]]'s director of [[compensation and benefits]], "As an employer there's a limit to what we can do for our employees. For us it made sense to have this service available, where our associates can reach out to somebody who knows the ins and outs of the health-care business."<ref>George, John (2–8 October 2009). "Health Advocate has the answers to health questions". Philadelphia Business Journal. http://philadelphia.bizjournals.com/philadelphia/stories/2009/10/05/focus2.html. Retrieved February 15, 2010.</ref> The company's services are available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.<ref>Burgess, Dave “Dealers sign with health advocacy service,” Western Business News November 2003</ref>

Those whose employers do not offer the service can purchase it from Health Advocate's direct-to-consumer arm [http://www.healthproponent.com/ Health Proponent].

